INST-3. Instruction and decision governance

INST-3.1. Instruction precedence and review
INST-3.1.1. When directives conflict, treat instruction files with higher leading numbers as authoritative because later documents supersede earlier ones by design.
INST-3.1.2. Read every instruction document before acting, and reread the full set whenever a new file appears so execution always reflects the latest guidance.
INST-3.1.3. During instruction recompilation, preserve all mandatory language from the sources and escalate unresolved conflicts instead of weakening requirements.

INST-3.2. Decision placement and immutability
INST-3.2.1. Document instruction-level guidance within the instruction directories and architecture guidance under `architecture/`, grouping related decisions when practical.
INST-3.2.2. Create new decision files for new topics instead of editing existing ones unless the user explicitly authorises an update.

INST-3.3. Decision file construction
INST-3.3.1. Name each decision file using the pattern `<N> - <DATETIME> - <SUBJECT>` where `<N>` matches the leading heading inside the file.
INST-3.3.2. Begin every file with `Authors:` followed by all contributors, including the user when content is user-authored, user-requested, or derived from their instructions.
INST-3.3.3. Structure content with numbered sections and subsections (for example `INST-3.3.4`) instead of unordered bullets to keep references stable.
INST-3.3.4. Assign unique subsection identifiers to every decision item so they can be cited precisely within other documents and code comments.

INST-3.4. Section prefix conventions
INST-3.4.1. Prefix every numbered section and subsection in top-level architecture decision files with `ARCH-<N>.` so all headings within `architecture/<N> - ...` begin with the matching identifier (for example `ARCH-1.1.` or `ARCH-1.4.2.`).
INST-3.4.2. When authoring new architecture decision documents, ensure every section you introduce uses the `ARCH-<N>.` prefix; do not retrofit previously published architecture files.
INST-3.4.3. Prefix every numbered section and subsection in instruction files with `INST-<N>.` so all headings appear as `INST-<N>.x`.
INST-3.4.4. Apply the `INST-<N>.` prefix to every section in newly authored instruction files; leave previously published instruction documents unchanged.
INST-3.4.5. When instruction content must evolve, create a new instruction document that supersedes the old one, retaining the `INST-<N>.` prefix and cross-referencing the retired guidance instead of editing the original file.

INST-3.5. History maintenance and commits
INST-3.5.1. Append a one-line summary for each new or updated decision file to the appropriate `HISTORY` file immediately after authoring the decision.
INST-3.5.2. Stage only the decision file and its HISTORY entry when committing so unrelated changes do not join the history.
INST-3.5.3. Begin instruction decision commit messages with `INST-` followed by a concise descriptor because instruction work is managed outside the task ledger.
INST-3.5.4. Begin architecture decision commit messages with `ARCH-` followed by a concise descriptor that identifies the decision being recorded.
INST-3.5.5. When another instruction mandates a specific commit message, execute `git commit` with that exact message and include only the referenced files.

INST-3.6. Instruction recompilation protocol
INST-3.6.1. When regrouping or recompiling instructions, preserve all mandatory language from the sources; escalate conflicts instead of weakening requirements.
INST-3.6.2. At the end of every recompiled file, include a numbered "Derived from" section listing all source instructions and clarifying the transformation when content is merged or expanded.
INST-3.6.3. Clarify ambiguities immediately by methodically scanning every relevant instruction for conflicting requirements, inconsistent wording, unclear scope, or misleading implications; document any uncertainty you cannot resolve, halt publication, and request explicit user guidance before proceeding.
INST-3.6.4. Publish recompiled instruction sets across logically grouped files so related guidance remains discoverable and maintainable.

INST-3.7. Instruction proposals
INST-3.7.1. Document reusable ideas as proposals in `instruction-proposals/`, applying the standard naming convention but listing only the proposer as the author.
INST-3.7.2. Do not enforce or commit proposals until the user explicitly approves them.
INST-3.7.3. After approval, migrate the accepted content into the canonical decision directories, update the relevant `HISTORY`, and commit following section INST-3.5.
INST-3.7.4. Leave rejected proposals in place unless the user instructs their removal.

